text.0:
A claim that Tanzanian opposition politician Tundu Lissu hosted a guest from the United States has MISSING CONTEXT.

:camera_with_flash: A photo which is part of the post shows Tundu Lissu with Donald Wright, the US ambassador to Tanzania: https://t.co/hClAOqmXIR
text.1:
A Facebook post claiming that the European Union has demanded Ethiopia release all political prisoners including Jawar Mohammed is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: An EU representative says the body has not made a public statement on the issue: https://t.co/ZtoxKIK00O
text.2:
A Facebook post with an image of a dilapidated road and text claiming that it shows the Nyendo-Masaka Road in :Uganda: is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The picture was first shared in 2016 and is from :Zimbabwe:: https://t.co/MKsXsgoSs3
text.3:
A tweet allegedly shared by Uganda’s deputy police spokesperson claiming that curfew roadblocks were set up to help some officers get school fees is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:warning_selector: The Twitter account that shared the claim does not belong to the deputy spokesperson: https://t.co/gxbFzHFPe5
text.4:
A Facebook photo showing a crowd of demonstrators carrying a banner branded ‘Male Sex Workers Association’ and claiming that “Ruto” supports their work is ALTERED.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The original photo does not refer to Kenya’s Deputy President William Ruto: https://t.co/jSpP0JoDCi
text.5:
A Facebook post with an image of a birth certificate allegedly belonging to Uganda’s President Yoweri Museveni is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The birth certificate claims to be from Case Hospital, which did not exist at the time the president was born: https://t.co/9zSaQjmW9G
text.7:
A screenshot bearing the name and image of Nairobi Governor Mike Sonko which dismisses Kenya's President Uhuru Kenyatta and other leaders in a derogatory language is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The account in the screenshot does not belong to Governor Sonko: https://t.co/UHeZ62tkgN
text.8:
A Facebook post with an image of pupils sitting on stones in what appears to be a flooded, mud-walled classroom claiming it was taken at a school in Busoga, Uganda, is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:camera_with_flash: The photo is from Kenya and appears in a report posted online in May 2019: https://t.co/buMTTPFe9Y
text.9:
An article shared on Facebook claiming that Kenya's Teachers Service Commission has dismissed 30 teachers has a FALSE HEADLINE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The TSC has recommended the removal of the teachers from its register for various offences, but is yet to dismiss them: https://t.co/kTqurIQEwv
text.10:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A Google form with instructions on how to apply for an immigration medical report form (IMM 1017E) in order to travel to Canada for work is fake.

:page_facing_up: The Google form is a doctored variation of the official guidelines: https://t.co/TQwsDApbAJ
text.11:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A memo announcing the resumption of studies at Kenya's Masinde Muliro University of Science and Technology on October 13 is fake.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The university has dismissed the memo, and none of the official reporting dates fall on October 13: https://t.co/uOP7A67HBN
text.12:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A document shared on social media claiming that Kenya's Teachers Service Commission has issued fresh instructions for teacher recruitment is fake.

:woman_teacher_medium-dark_skin_tone: The TSC has dismissed the document and says the recruitment process remains on course: https://t.co/uOP7A67HBN
text.13:
An Instagram post claiming that wildfires have broken out on Mount Kilimanjaro is :white_heavy_check_mark: TRUE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: A Tanzania National Parks official confirmed that there was a fire burning through a section of Africa’s tallest mountain: https://t.co/QW4NPCgUyE
